---
// FAQ Section - addressing the five real objections
---

<section class="faq-section section bg-light">
  <div class="container">

    <div class="faq-header">
      <h2>FAQs</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-grid">

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          How is this different from hiring a HubSpot consultant?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            Most HubSpot consultants focus on one thing: making HubSpot work. We focus on making your entire revenue engine work - which sometimes means fixing HubSpot, sometimes fixing your sales process, and sometimes integrating systems that have nothing to do with HubSpot.
          </p>
          <p>
            We also have someone who's actually closed enterprise deals, so we know firsthand what it costs an operator when the tools don't work. That perspective isn't common in implementation.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          We already have a RevOps person. Why do we need you?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            We're not here to replace your RevOps person - we extend their capacity. Most internal RevOps leaders are underwater in tickets and don't have bandwidth for the strategic work they know needs to happen.
          </p>
          <p>
            We come in as allies. We handle the heavy projects they've been deferring, document everything, and hand it back in a state they can own and maintain.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          What does the $100K guarantee actually mean?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            We run our Deep-Scan against your CRM. If we don't find at least $100K in recoverable pipeline - orphaned deals, zombie opportunities, reactivation candidates - you don't pay the $1,500 fee.
          </p>
          <p>
            We're confident because the math is consistent. The average mid-market B2B company has 15-25% of revenue leaking due to data issues. We find it and show you exactly where it is.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <!-- REVISED: Removed "Can you really..." defensive framing -->
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          What makes you different from a RevOps firm that also does sales consulting?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            The difference is that our sales expertise is earned, not adjacent. Jaron has rebuilt revenue infrastructure for 15+ companies - 400K+ records migrated, 75% CRM cost reductions. Joseph has closed $900K ARR enterprise deals at Checkout.com and built $2M in new pipeline.
          </p>
          <p>
            When we build a system, it gets stress-tested by someone who's had to sell with broken tools. When we design a sales process, it gets implemented by someone who knows how to make CRMs actually work.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          How fast can you start?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            Deep-Scans typically start within a week of signing. Full Pipeline Re-Architecture projects kick off within 2 weeks.
          </p>
          <p>
            We're a focused team - no 6-month discovery phases. If you need to show the board progress in 90 days, that's the kind of timeline we're designed for.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          What do we actually own at the end? Are we stuck without you?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            You own everything, and no.
          </p>
          <p>
            Every integration we build, every workflow we codify, every definition of what your data means in your specific business - all of it lives in your infrastructure, not ours. We document as we go, and we hand it back in a state your team can maintain and build on without us.
          </p>
          <p>
            The other thing worth knowing: the system compounds. Every question your team asks, every workflow that gets promoted to shared infrastructure, makes the next one faster and cheaper. Most consultants leave you with a deck and a to-do list. We leave you with a revenue engine that gets smarter whether we're in the room or not.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          Is our data safe going into AI systems?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            Yes - and the architecture is specifically designed to keep it that way.
          </p>
          <p>
            Your data never leaves your own infrastructure. The AI layer we build sits in the middle as middleware - it routes requests and returns answers, but your credentials and your data stay server-side on your own deployment. Read-only by default. Every integration that touches your systems goes through a QA review and an explicit approval before it goes live.
          </p>
          <p>
            We're not feeding your pipeline into a third-party AI that learns from your data. We're building you a controlled, governed layer that uses AI to answer questions about your own data - on your terms.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">
          Do we have to change our current tools?
        </summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>
            No. We build on top of what you already have.
          </p>
          <p>
            HubSpot, Salesforce, Gong, Salesloft, Apollo, Clay, Stripe, BigQuery - if your team is already using it, we connect it. The whole point is to make your existing stack work together as one system, not rip it out and start over.
          </p>
          <p>
            The only question we ask is whether your current tools are the right ones for what you're trying to do. Sometimes they are. Sometimes there's a cheaper or better fit. But that's a recommendation, not a requirement - and it's always your call.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .faq-section {
    background-color: var(--section-light-bg);
  }

  .faq-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
  }

  .faq-header h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 900;
    color: var(--heading-color);
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .faq-grid {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-md);
  }

  .faq-item {
    background-color: var(--card-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    border-radius: var(--card-radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color var(--transition-base), box-shadow var(--transition-base);
  }

  .faq-item:hover,
  .faq-item[open] {
    border-color: var(--sky-blue);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .faq-question {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--heading-color);
    padding: var(--space-lg);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-md);
  }

  .faq-question::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .faq-question::after {
    content: '+';
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--sky-blue);
    flex-shrink: 0;
    transition: transform var(--transition-base);
  }

  .faq-item[open] .faq-question::after {
    transform: rotate(45deg);
  }

  .faq-answer {
    padding: 0 var(--space-lg) var(--space-lg);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    margin-top: calc(-1 * var(--space-sm));
    padding-top: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .faq-answer p {
    font-family: var(--font-body);
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--muted-text);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .faq-answer p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
</style>
